    "--shiki-dark": "#E1E4E8"
  }}>{"}"}</_components.span></_components.span></_components.code></_components.pre>{"\n"}<_components.p>{"Default budget: 10,000 node expansions, 5,000 ms. If the budget is exhausted before finding a complete plan, the planner returns the best partial plan it found — the path with the lowest "}<_components.code>{"f"}</_components.code>{" score at the frontier. This is the “anytime” property: even a partial plan is useful for escalation context."}</_components.p>{"\n"}<_components.p><_components.em><_components.em>{"Weighted A"}</_components.em>{":"}</_components.em>{"*"}</_components.p>{"\n"}<_components.p>{"When "}<_components.code>{"weight > 1.0"}</_components.code>{", "}<_components.code>{"f(n) = g(n) + weight × h(n)"}</_components.code>{". This inflates the heuristic, making the search greedier. It finds plans faster but may not find the optimal one. This is useful when time budget is tight and “good enough” is acceptable."}</_components.p>{"\n"}<_components.p><_components.strong>{"HTN integration:"}</_components.strong></_components.p>{"\n"}<_components.p>{"The planner doesn’t work directly from the raw action graph. The HTN decomposer first traverses the task hierarchy to produce the candidate primitive action set for the current goal. This scopes the search to actions that are relevant to the current objective — reducing the effective branching factor and making search tractable."}</_components.p>{"\n"}<_components.hr />{"\n"}<_components.h2 id={toc[4].id}>{toc[4].value}</_components.h2>{"\n"}<_components.p>{"Ava (the primary agent) serves as the L2 tier — the fallback when A* planning fails or is out of budget."}</_components.p>{"\n"}<_components.p><_components.em><_components.em>{"When A"}</_components.em>{" fails:"}</_components.em>{"*"}</_components.p>{"\n"}<_components.ul>{"\n"}<_components.li>{"The goal cannot be satisfied by any sequence of known actions (the action graph lacks a path)"}</_components.li>{"\n"}<_components.li>{"The search budget is exhausted before finding a plan"}</_components.li>{"\n"}<_components.li>{"The estimated cost exceeds the L1 threshold ($1.00)"}</_components.li>{"\n"}</_components.ul>{"\n"}<_components.p><_components.strong>{"What Ava brings:"}</_components.strong></_components.p>{"\n"}<_components.p>{"A* is a systematic but closed-world planner. It can only use actions explicitly defined in the action graph. It cannot:"}</_components.p>{"\n"}<_components.ul>{"\n"}<_components.li>{"Reason about goals expressed in natural language"}</_components.li>{"\n"}<_components.li>{"Consult documentation or past incidents"}</_components.li>{"\n"}<_components.li>{"Propose new action types not in the graph"}</_components.li>{"\n"}<_components.li>{"Weigh ambiguous trade-offs"}</_components.li>{"\n"}</_components.ul>{"\n"}<_components.p>{"Ava operates on the full context of the incident: the violation event, the world state snapshot, recent board state, prior similar incidents from Qdrant. Ava can call tools not in the L1 action graph, ask clarifying questions, and return a prose explanation alongside an action recommendation."}</_components.p>{"\n"}<_components.p><_components.strong>{"Why not always use Ava?"}</_components.strong></_components.p>{"\n"}<_components.p>{"Cost and latency. A full Ava session runs at claude-sonnet or claude-opus token rates. For a routine “auth service is degraded, restart it” correction, that is 10–100× more expensive than a L0 rule execution. The tiered architecture ensures Ava is reserved for situations where its reasoning capability is genuinely needed — not wasted on deterministic tasks."}</_components.p>{"\n"}<_components.p><_components.strong>{"The boundary:"}</_components.strong></_components.p>{"\n"}<_components.p>{"The L0L1Bridge is the handoff point. L0 tries its rule matcher first. If it fails, the bridge constructs an "}<_components.code>{"L0Context"}</_components.code>{" (current state, goal, reason for failure) and passes it to the L1 planner. If L1 also fails (no plan found, budget exceeded), the calling code escalates to L2 (Ava) via the standard A2A routing path."}</_components.p>{"\n"}<_components.pre tabIndex="0" data-language="plaintext" data-word-wrap="" data-pagefind-ignore="all"><_components.code><_components.span><_components.span>{"L0 fails → L0Context constructed → L1Planner.planFromContext()"}</_components.span></_components.span>{"\n"}<_components.span><_components.span>{"                                          │"}</_components.span></_components.span>{"\n"}<_components.span><_components.span>{"                                    Plan found? ──Yes──► Execute"}</_components.span></_components.span>{"\n"}<_components.span><_components.span>{"                                          │ No"}</_components.span></_components.span>{"\n"}<_components.span><_components.span>{"                                    Escalate to L2 (Ava)"}</_components.span></_components.span></_components.code></_components.pre>{"\n"}<_components.p>{"This means Ava always receives the L0 failure reason and the partial plan (if any) as context — it starts from the planner’s best attempt, not from scratch."}</_components.p></>;
}
